        "Description/Abstract": "&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;We investigate the effect of admission to a top-quality, tuition-free university on future criminal charges. Using data on students' application to a public university and the universe of criminal records in Brazil, we document that admitted students are 69% less likely to be prosecuted in the decade following application. This effect is mostly driven by a reduction in violent crimes among low-income men. Changes in educational attainment, incapacitation, financial distress, unemployment, and earnings do not explain our findings. Our results suggest that the returns to expanding access of low-income students to high-quality universities extend far beyond job opportunities.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;",
